9.A user types www.google.com into their browser, but the browser displays a ”Server Not Found” error, even though the internet connection
is active. However, accessing the site via 142.250.190.46 works. Diagnose the problem and explain the underlying technology that failed.
The problem is a failure in the Domain Name System (DNS). While our internet connection is active, our browser cannot translate 
human-readable domain name (www.google.com) into the numerical IP address (142.250.190.46) necessary for communication.

The failure is confirmed because:
Accessing the site by its IP address (142.250.190.46) works, meaning the Google server is operational and your internet connection is 
functional.
Accessing the site by its domain name (www.google.com) fails, indicating the step of finding that IP address from the name is not working 

The underlying technology that failed are :-
-Local DNS Cache Issue: Our computer might have outdated or corrupted DNS information stored locally.
-ISP's DNS Server is Down or Misconfigured: The DNS server provided by your ISP may be experiencing a temporary outage or configuration
 error .
- Network Configuration Errors: Problems with your router or firewall settings might be blocking DNS traffic.
- Malware or Security Software: Sometimes, security software or malware can interfere with DNS requests, potentially redirecting them or
  blocking them entirely. 

